1. Spring Boot Fundamentals â€“ Complete Interview Notes
1. What is Spring Boot?
Spring Boot is a framework built on top of Spring Framework that simplifies the development of standalone, production-ready Spring applications with minimal configuration.

Interview one-liner
â€œSpring Boot simplifies Spring application development by providing auto-configuration, embedded servers, and opinionated defaults.â€

2. Problems with Traditional Spring (Why Spring Boot Came)
Traditional Spring Issues âŒ

Too much XML configuration
Manual dependency management
Boilerplate code
External server setup (Tomcat, Jetty)
Complex project setup
Steep learning curve

Example (Traditional Spring XML)
<bean id="userService" class="com.app.UserService">
    <property name="repo" ref="userRepo"/>
</bean>


ğŸ‘‰ Too verbose, error-prone, and hard to maintain.
3. How Spring Boot Solves These Problems âœ…
| Traditional Spring | Spring Boot        |
| ------------------ | ------------------ |
| XML config         | Java + annotations |
| Manual setup       | Auto-configuration |
| External server    | Embedded server    |
| Long setup time    | Ready in minutes   |
| Boilerplate        | Convention-based   |

4. Key Features of Spring Boot (ğŸ”¥ MUST KNOW)
4.1 Auto-Configuration

Automatically configures beans based on:
Classpath dependencies
Application properties
Environment

@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);
    }
}

âœ” No explicit configuration
âœ” Smart defaults

4.2 Starter Dependencies
Predefined dependency bundles.
spring-boot-starter-web

Includes:
Spring MVC
Embedded Tomcat
Jackson
Validation

4.3 Embedded Servers
Tomcat (default)
Jetty
Undertow
java -jar app.jar

âœ” No WAR
âœ” No external deployment

4.4 Production-Ready Features

Using Actuator:
Health
Metrics
Monitoring

4.5 Externalized Configuration
server.port=8081
spring.application.name=demo-app

âœ” Same code â†’ different environments

5. Spring vs Spring MVC vs Spring Boot (ğŸ”¥ Interview Favorite)
| Feature     | Spring        | Spring MVC | Spring Boot |
| ----------- | ------------- | ---------- | ----------- |
| Type        | Framework     | Web module | Framework   |
| Purpose     | Core features | Web apps   | Rapid dev   |
| Config      | Heavy         | Medium     | Minimal     |
| Server      | External      | External   | Embedded    |
| Auto-config | âŒ             | âŒ          | âœ…           |

Interview one-liner
â€œSpring MVC is part of Spring; Spring Boot sits on top of Spring to simplify configuration.â€

6. Opinionated Defaults (ğŸ”¥ Very Important)
What does â€œOpinionatedâ€ mean?
Spring Boot makes decisions for you based on best practices.

Examples:
Uses Tomcat as default server
Uses Jackson for JSON
Uses HikariCP for connection pool
Uses application.properties for config

ğŸ‘‰ You can override defaults if needed.

7. Convention over Configuration
Meaning
Follow standard conventions instead of writing explicit configuration.
Example

If you add:
spring-boot-starter-web
Spring Boot automatically:
Enables Spring MVC
Registers DispatcherServlet
Configures Jackson
Starts Tomcat

âœ” Less code
âœ” Faster development

8. Simple Spring Boot Example (With Output)
Controller
@RestController
public class HelloController {

    @GetMapping("/hello")
    public String hello() {
        return "Hello Spring Boot";
    }
}

Output (Browser / Postman)
Hello Spring Boot

âœ” No XML
âœ” No servlet config
âœ” No dispatcher setup

